1
00:00:00,989 --> 00:00:05,709
Most of Forex or stock market traders, in
one form or another, use different types of

2
00:00:05,709 --> 00:00:07,959
moving averages while trading.

3
00:00:07,959 --> 00:00:12,980
But the main problem of all indicators built
on the mathematics of averages is the lagging

4
00:00:12,980 --> 00:00:14,469
factor.

5
00:00:14,469 --> 00:00:18,500
Traders use indicators based on averages to
build dynamic lines of support/resistance

6
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:22,790
and to evaluate the strength of price momentum.

7
00:00:22,790 --> 00:00:28,119
Their main disadvantage lies in the method
of calculation: since moving averages are

8
00:00:28,119 --> 00:00:35,700
calculated based on past prices (for a certain
period of time or number of bars), the calculated

9
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:42,120
line reduces price fluctuations, but will
always lag behind real price.

10
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:46,970
For this reason, Alan Hull, an Australian
financial analyst and trader, proposed an

11
00:00:46,970 --> 00:00:52,750
improved version of the moving average, providing
smooth indicators in the construction and

12
00:00:52,750 --> 00:00:57,220
almost completely eliminating the negative
effect of lagging.

13
00:00:57,220 --> 00:01:01,690
The hull moving average is an extremely fast
and smooth moving average.

14
00:01:01,690 --> 00:01:09,590
In fact, the HMA almost eliminates lag altogether
and manages to improve smoothing at the same

15
00:01:09,590 --> 00:01:10,600
time.

16
00:01:10,600 --> 00:01:15,939
Its calculation is rather complex but I’ll
try to keep it simple, so you’ll understand

17
00:01:15,939 --> 00:01:20,299
why this type of moving average is better
than the classic ones.

18
00:01:20,299 --> 00:01:25,119
The hull moving average formula makes use
of the weighted moving average (wma).

19
00:01:25,119 --> 00:01:32,200
It emphasizes recent prices over older ones,
resulting in a fast-acting yet smooth moving

20
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:36,090
average that can be used to identify the prevailing
market trend.

21
00:01:36,090 --> 00:01:43,639
The HMA employs weighted moving averages and
dampens the smoothing effect (and resulting

22
00:01:43,639 --> 00:01:51,630
lag) by using the square root of the period
instead of the actual period itself.

23
00:01:51,630 --> 00:01:56,549
For clarity of the analysis, let’s compare
the hull moving average indicator with a simple

24
00:01:56,549 --> 00:01:57,549
moving average.

25
00:01:57,549 --> 00:02:03,100
So we added a 20 period simple moving average
and a 20 period hull moving average.

26
00:02:03,100 --> 00:02:09,950
First, you immediately notice that the hull
ma is faster than the simple moving average.

27
00:02:09,950 --> 00:02:15,720
Also, is more reactive to price action, because
it has less lag.

28
00:02:15,720 --> 00:02:21,840
The simple moving average is way behind the
hull one, with delayed entries and exits.

29
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:28,520
The hull ma is providing signals well ahead
as compared to the simple moving average indicator.

30
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:32,410
How to use hull ma?

31
00:02:32,410 --> 00:02:37,030
For those who use price action to trade the
markets, there are mixed opinion about the

32
00:02:37,030 --> 00:02:38,790
use of moving averages.

33
00:02:38,790 --> 00:02:42,900
I mean, why would you use them if price is
your indicator?

34
00:02:42,900 --> 00:02:48,680
Well, let me explain why the hull ma can add
to your trading arsenal.

35
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:56,530
I use hull moving averages in two basic ways:
– to identify a change in trend or the strength

36
00:02:56,530 --> 00:02:58,040
of a trend.

37
00:02:58,040 --> 00:03:01,290
– as dynamic levels of support and resistance.

38
00:03:01,290 --> 00:03:07,580
Hull mas can provide insight to possible trend
changes as well as showing traders an indication

39
00:03:07,580 --> 00:03:10,770
of the strength of an existing trend.

40
00:03:10,770 --> 00:03:15,280
Using a hull ma to determine the trend of
an instrument is great… during trending

41
00:03:15,280 --> 00:03:22,100
moments, but during consolidation periods,
relying on mas all-too-often causes traders

42
00:03:22,100 --> 00:03:24,830
to get whipped out of trades.

43
00:03:24,830 --> 00:03:29,070
But we’ll discuss more on that later.

44
00:03:29,070 --> 00:03:33,010
How this indicator works:
First, to define a trend:

45
00:03:33,010 --> 00:03:37,530
A longer period hull ma may be used to identify
trend.

46
00:03:37,530 --> 00:03:44,420
If the hull ma is rising, the prevailing trend
is rising, indicating it may be better to

47
00:03:44,420 --> 00:03:45,870
enter long positions.

48
00:03:45,870 --> 00:03:52,320
If the hull ma is falling, the prevailing
trend is also falling, indicating it may be

49
00:03:52,320 --> 00:03:55,200
better to enter short positions.

50
00:03:55,200 --> 00:04:08,510
Here are a few examples, based on price action
and a hull moving average.

51
00:04:08,510 --> 00:04:22,280
So, the change of slope of the hull moving
average indicator tells you to be ready to

52
00:04:22,280 --> 00:04:23,530
buy or sell.

53
00:04:23,530 --> 00:04:27,150
If the slope starts to point up, get ready
to buy.

54
00:04:27,150 --> 00:04:30,750
If the slope starts to point down, get ready
to sell.

55
00:04:30,750 --> 00:04:37,880
In fact, i would say the hull ma works even
better as a reversal filter, and, therefore,

56
00:04:37,880 --> 00:04:43,319
its exit signals are more reliable at times
than the entry.

57
00:04:43,319 --> 00:04:47,180
Now what about when the price crosses above
and below the moving average?

58
00:04:47,180 --> 00:04:53,379
I saw a lot of traders trading the hull ma
in a wrong way, trying to scalp or day trade

59
00:04:53,379 --> 00:04:55,930
when the price crossed above and below the
ma.

60
00:04:55,930 --> 00:05:02,030
Here’s an important tip: the "breakthrough"
by the price of the line of the hull moving

61
00:05:02,030 --> 00:05:07,000
average indicator itself shouldn’t be perceived
as the market signal.

62
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:12,469
Because of the small lag, it is difficult
to generate buy/sell signals on the crossovers

63
00:05:12,469 --> 00:05:15,190
of hull ma and price.

64
00:05:15,190 --> 00:05:17,960
Have a look at this example of a strong trend.

65
00:05:17,960 --> 00:05:22,599
Let’s consider that you aim to sell every
time the price crosses the hull moving average

66
00:05:22,599 --> 00:05:24,080
to the downside.

67
00:05:24,080 --> 00:05:28,889
Although you are protected in a small way
by the strong trend, you see that the signals

68
00:05:28,889 --> 00:05:31,169
are not as accurate.

69
00:05:31,169 --> 00:05:35,729
The price cuts through the moving average
with ease, practically stopping out the traders

70
00:05:35,729 --> 00:05:38,379
on the other side of the moving average.

71
00:05:38,379 --> 00:05:42,909
But if you just followed the slope of the
hull ma like i said before, you wouldn’t

72
00:05:42,909 --> 00:05:47,870
need to enter so many times in the market,
because the slope was pointing down the whole

73
00:05:47,870 --> 00:05:48,870
time.

74
00:05:48,870 --> 00:05:53,759
You got in the trade once, captured the move
and got out when the hook of the moving average

75
00:05:53,759 --> 00:05:55,599
turned upwards.

76
00:05:55,599 --> 00:05:59,219
And that’s the positive scenario, of a trending
market.

77
00:05:59,219 --> 00:06:04,650
Look what happens when you want to trade price
crossovers of the hull ma in a range.

78
00:06:04,650 --> 00:06:06,610
Things can get ugly pretty quick.

79
00:06:06,610 --> 00:06:09,529
Look at how many false signals this strategy
offered.

80
00:06:09,529 --> 00:06:11,620
It’s a trader’s nightmare.

81
00:06:11,620 --> 00:06:15,800
As soon as you enter a trade, it immediately
retraces in the opposite direction.

82
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:21,259
So, if you want to preserve your capital in
long run, avoid trading crossovers between

83
00:06:21,259 --> 00:06:24,940
the price and hull ma.

84
00:06:24,940 --> 00:06:28,840
What about the crossover between 2 hull moving
averages?

85
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:31,219
I would ignore those signals also.

86
00:06:31,219 --> 00:06:35,440
If you watched my other moving averages videos
on my channel, you know that I’m not a big

87
00:06:35,440 --> 00:06:40,289
fan of crossovers, because in the long term,
they will slowly diminish your account.

88
00:06:40,289 --> 00:06:45,660
Yes, there are traders that rely exclusively
on moving average crossovers, but I’m not

89
00:06:45,660 --> 00:06:47,499
one of them, I’ve experienced more losers
than winners trying to come up with a magic

90
00:06:47,499 --> 00:06:48,499
crossover.

91
00:06:48,499 --> 00:06:52,780
So let’s take a look at some charts to see
what a crossover of 2 hull ma tells us.

92
00:06:52,780 --> 00:07:00,749
We added a short term one, a 7 hull ma and
a longer term one, a 50 hull ma.

93
00:07:00,749 --> 00:07:04,409
First scenario: trading crossovers on trending
markets.

94
00:07:04,409 --> 00:07:06,319
So, what do we see?

95
00:07:06,319 --> 00:07:12,639
Yes, a couple of good signals, but if you
missed the good ones and entered here, for

96
00:07:12,639 --> 00:07:15,469
example, you got stopped out quickly.

97
00:07:15,469 --> 00:07:17,599
Too many bad signals.

98
00:07:17,599 --> 00:07:19,330
What about ranging markets?

99
00:07:19,330 --> 00:07:25,439
Well, it’s almost impossible to be consistent
trading crossovers when there isn’t a trend.

100
00:07:25,439 --> 00:07:30,080
I don’t see how you could avoid all these
false signals and have a positive balance

101
00:07:30,080 --> 00:07:32,129
at the end of the trading session.

102
00:07:32,129 --> 00:07:37,759
How i would trade with 2 hull ma on my chart?

103
00:07:37,759 --> 00:07:41,050
I told you before: the slope is all you need.

104
00:07:41,050 --> 00:07:46,939
You have the long term 50 ma, and the short
term ma, the 7 period,

105
00:07:46,939 --> 00:07:51,900
The shorter period hull ma may be used for
entry signals in the direction of the prevailing

106
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:52,900
trend.

107
00:07:52,900 --> 00:07:59,039
A long entry signal, when the prevailing trend
is rising, occurs when the 7 hull ma turns

108
00:07:59,039 --> 00:08:05,729
up, and a short entry signal, when the prevailing
trend is falling, occurs when the 7 hull ma

109
00:08:05,729 --> 00:08:06,800
turns down.

110
00:08:06,800 --> 00:08:14,189
You don’t search for crossovers; you search
for both the ma to indicate the same direction.

111
00:08:14,189 --> 00:08:20,610
So if the 50hull ma is pointing upwards, you
carefully watch for the hook of the 7 ma to

112
00:08:20,610 --> 00:08:22,169
shift upward.

113
00:08:22,169 --> 00:08:23,169
Is this strategy perfect?

114
00:08:23,169 --> 00:08:27,909
Of course not, but you’ll enter the trade
early, compared to a crossover.

115
00:08:27,909 --> 00:08:33,080
Also, it goes without saying, but you should
aim to trade during trending scenarios.

116
00:08:33,080 --> 00:08:39,959
So always look for higher higher and higher
lows, and lower lows and lower highs.

117
00:08:39,959 --> 00:08:55,449
Here are a few examples of potential entries
using 2 moving averages.

118
00:08:55,449 --> 00:09:11,170
Now, a serious drawback of hull moving average
is the fact that as a moving average indicator

119
00:09:11,170 --> 00:09:13,790
is not quite consistent with reality.

120
00:09:13,790 --> 00:09:19,300
If you are accustomed to using standard moving
averages for trends searching, the HMA indicator

121
00:09:19,300 --> 00:09:24,530
will not be a full replacement: it shows only
the general direction of market trend, but

122
00:09:24,530 --> 00:09:29,470
it is completely unclear when it is safe (and
profitable) to open a trade.

123
00:09:29,470 --> 00:09:34,490
Adding the HMA only tells you that you can
safely open a short position when its slope

124
00:09:34,490 --> 00:09:37,580
is down and a long trade when the slope is
up.

125
00:09:37,580 --> 00:09:43,720
That’s why hull moving average indicator
without additional filters is not recommended.

126
00:09:43,720 --> 00:09:49,029
As always rely first on price action, support
and resistance, and then confirm your bias

127
00:09:49,029 --> 00:09:50,530
with the hull ma.

